1 to 11 Fleet Place, east side (as seen across clearing), south from Tillary Street (left). Also shown is Tillary Street, south side, east from Fleet Place to Hudson Ave. At the S.E. corner of the latter streets is a beer garden, typifying the neighborhood.

July 1, 1934.

P. L. Sperr.

17 Fleet Street, at the N.E. corner of Willoughby Street (right), showing a 3-story building whose store is occupied by a colored organization, St. John's Fire Baptist Church of Christ in America. On the left appears a view eastward on Fleet Street. In the background is the Myrtle Ave. (B.M.T.) Elevated line, and beyond it an old church building. July 22, 1934.

P. L. Sperr.

Willoughby Street, south side, east from Fleet Street, beyond Hudson Ave., and towards Fort Greene Park. On Hudson Ave., may be seen the Fifth Ave., B.M.T. Elevated Lines.

July 1, 1934.

P. L. Sperr.

95 Fleet Place, east side, between Willoughby Street and Myrtle Avenue, showing an abandoned tenement, view 2 showing the rear. These photographs were taken to show primarily bad housing conditions still existent in the borough.
